### **Descriptive Statistics Concepts (with 2-line descriptions)**  

1ï¸âƒ£ **Mean (Average)** â†’ The sum of all values divided by the number of values. It is sensitive to outliers.  

2ï¸âƒ£ **Median** â†’ The middle value in a sorted dataset. It is more robust to outliers than the mean.  

3ï¸âƒ£ **Mode** â†’ The most frequently occurring value in a dataset. A dataset can have **one (unimodal), two (bimodal), or more modes**.  

4ï¸âƒ£ **Range** â†’ The difference between the maximum and minimum values. It gives a measure of data spread.  

5ï¸âƒ£ **Variance** â†’ Measures how far each data point is from the mean, calculated as the average squared deviation from the mean.  

6ï¸âƒ£ **Standard Deviation** â†’ The square root of variance, indicating how spread out the data points are from the mean.  

7ï¸âƒ£ **Interquartile Range (IQR)** â†’ The difference between the **75th percentile (Q3) and 25th percentile (Q1)**, measuring data dispersion while ignoring outliers.  

8ï¸âƒ£ **Skewness** â†’ Measures the asymmetry of data distribution; **positive skew** means a longer right tail, **negative skew** means a longer left tail.  

9ï¸âƒ£ **Kurtosis** â†’ Measures the "tailedness" of the distribution; **high kurtosis** means more extreme outliers, **low kurtosis** means fewer.  

ğŸ”Ÿ **Summary Statistics (`describe()`)** â†’ Provides a quick overview of count, mean, std deviation, min, max, and percentiles of data.  

